<section xml:id="sec_Rings_Hints">
  <title>Hints for
  <q>Introduction to Rings</q>
  exercises</title>
  <p>
    <xref ref="exercise_Rings_Iso_Z10_to_Z5">Exercise</xref>: Look at the Cayley tables and imagine that the tables contain only the first element in each pair.
  </p>
  <p>
    <xref ref="exercise_Rings_Z3_homo">Exercise</xref>: This is similar to <xref ref="exercise_Rings_Iso_Z10_to_Z5">Exercise</xref>.
  </p>
  <p>
    <xref ref="exercise_Rings_abc_iso">Exercise</xref>: Part (b): Check if <m>f</m> has an inverse.
  </p>
  <p>
    <xref ref="exercise_Rings_ringIsPrId">Exercise</xref>: Can you think of an element in <m>R</m> that generates all of <m>R</m>?
  </p>
  <p>
    <xref ref="exercise_Rings_zerodivisor">Exercise</xref>: Take the expression <m>ab=0</m> and multiply both sides on the left by <m>a^{-1}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    <xref ref="exercise_Rings_zdzp">Exercise</xref>: Use <xref ref="proposition_Rings_zerodivisor">Proposition</xref>
    part b and remember that <m>\mathbb{Z}_p</m> is a field.
  </p>
</section>